  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "We are participating in exponential growth in artificial intelligence and machine learning (hereafter: AI/ML) applications, using them, or being data subjects of them, as they move out of the lab into the world, impacting everyday lives.",
    "Consequently, there has also been increased attention to algorithmic bias and harm enacted by AI applications (Benjamin, 2021).",
    "There is now a growing call for AI literacy (e.g., Long & Magerko, 2021; Touretzky et al., 2018) and for all K-12 students and teachers to be prepared to understand, use and critique AI applications.",
    "However, to date, most AI in education efforts have concentrated on what has been called artificialteachers, artificial-tutors, and artificial co-learners, positioning learners as recipients of instruction from AI agents or collaborators with AI agents (Ouyang & Jiao, 2021).",
    "In current discussions, one perspective has received much less attention: how learners create, train, test and research AI applications."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
